al rollercoaster and using sneaky tactics to obscure that reality. With unprecedented access to interviews, surveys, and hundreds of thousands of crowdfunding cases across North America, Erik Schneiderhan and Martin Lukk take on pressing questions with critical insight: When do we turn to others for help? Who succeeds and who fails in the digital crowd? Whom do these sites benefit? Ultimately, the failure of GoFundMe and others is emblematic of the inability of the for-profit sector and Big Tech to engineer an end to social inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCharitieszCanada2DLC. 0aCharitieszCanada. 0aCharitieszUnited States2DLC. 0aCharitieszUnited States. 0aCrowd fundingzCanada2DLC. 0aCrowd fundingzCanada. 0aCrowd fundingzUnited States2DLC. 0aCrowd fundingzUnited States. 0aElectronic fund raisingzCanada2DLC. 0aElectronic fund raisingzCanada. 0aElectronic fund raisingzUnited States2DLC. 0aElectronic fund raisingzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aCrowdfunding.  aDigital Age.  aGoFundMe.  aInequality.  aSocial Welfare.  aUnited States.  aWelfare State.1 aLukk, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363693440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503636934423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503636934/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles